@lacm81 You're reducing voltage, which may impact stability. So cores are made to a certain standard, some are a bit better quality, some are a bit worse. For them to all work the same way, more voltage is put in them than required, to maintain stability. If the voltage is too low, then capacitors are not filled fully before they are discharged, leading to instability and crashes.

If you have a good quality core, you can very significantly reduce the voltage. If the core is of poor quality, you might only get 10% of an undervolt (or whatever the minimum margin is that AMD uses).

Still, every core should be able to be undervolted. But, there's another issue, which is core degradation. With use, cores degrade naturally, and an undervolt that was stable 2 years ago may become unstable 2 years later. If that happens, you need to increase the voltage to maintain stability. Undervolting the core should slow down core degradation, but it won't completely stop it.

